Changes since v1:
-Change the variable [length] type to unsigned, as Eric Dumazet suggested.
Changes since v2:
-Don't change exthdrlen type in ip6_make_skb, as Paolo Abeni suggested.
Changes since v3:
-Don't change ulen type in udpv6_sendmsg and l2tp_ip6_sendmsg, as
Jakub Kicinski suggested.

[Davide Benini's notes]
Changing int to size_t in ip6_append_data cannot be done, as that would change the kABI; how can we avoid this?

The UBSAN overflow control is indicating this call trace:

UBSAN: signed-integer-overflow in net/ipv6/ip6_output.c:1489:19
2147479552 + 8567 cannot be represented in type 'int'
CPU: 0 PID: 253 Comm: err Not tainted 5.16.0+ #1
Hardware name: linux,dummy-virt (DT)
Call trace:
  dump_backtrace+0x214/0x230
  show_stack+0x30/0x78
  dump_stack_lvl+0xf8/0x118
  dump_stack+0x18/0x30
  ubsan_epilogue+0x18/0x60
  handle_overflow+0xd0/0xf0
  __ubsan_handle_add_overflow+0x34/0x44
  __ip6_append_data.isra.48+0x1598/0x1688
  ip6_append_data+0x128/0x260
  udpv6_sendmsg+0x680/0xdd0
  inet6_sendmsg+0x54/0x90
  sock_sendmsg+0x70/0x88

In udpv6_sendmsg, ip6_append_data() is called with:
err = ip6_append_data(sk, getfrag, msg, ulen, sizeof(struct udphdr),
                              &ipc6, fl6, (struct rt6_info *)dst,
                              corkreq ? msg->msg_flags|MSG_MORE : msg->msg_flags);

where
int ulen = len;
(len is a size_t)

So len has already been cast to int, with a potential loss of data from the
64-bit size_t to the 32-bit int; moreover, there is a signed/unsigned mismatch.

The v2 version of the patch (5 versions have been made, the last one being the
actual patch) changed the ulen to size_t; that makes sense.
But in v3 they claimed that the change is not needed, as it will not overflow.
So let's consider the cast safe
So, where is the offending line? Let's check the call trace
udpv6_sendmsg()
    ip6_append_data()

1)
int udpv6_sendmsg(struct sock *sk, struct msghdr *msg, size_t len) {
...
int ulen = len;  //this is considered safe in upstream discussion
...
ulen += sizeof(struct udphdr); //considered safe in upstream discussion, it will not overflow

Here the code will call either:
   ip6_make_skb(sk, getfrag, msg, ulen, ...
   ip6_append_data(sk, getfrag, msg, ulen, ...

2)
int ip6_append_data(struct sock *sk,
                    int getfrag(void *from, char *to, int offset, int len,
                                int odd, struct sk_buff *skb),
                    void *from, int length, int transhdrlen,

...
length += exthdrlen;


The above could overflow; the patch changes

 int ip6_append_data(struct sock *sk,
 		    int getfrag(void *from, char *to, int offset, int len,
 				int odd, struct sk_buff *skb),
-		    void *from, int length, int transhdrlen,
+		    void *from, size_t length, int transhdrlen,

avoiding the overflow of the
length += exthdrlen;


But, if we consider steps at 1) safe, it means changing in ip6_append_data the
parameter type from int to size_t will not avoid a potential loss of data, as
the value passed is already an int, granted to be correct. So we can work
inside the function, casting length to size_t before adding exthdrlen:
size_t ulength = length;
ulength += exthdrlen;

and go on using ulength

This avoids changing the function prototype and kABI
[end of notes]

Reported-by: Hulk Robot <hulkci@huawei.com>
Signed-off-by: Wang Yufen <wangyufen@huawei.com>
Link: https://lore.kernel.org/r/20220607120028.845916-1-wangyufen@huawei.com
Signed-off-by: Jakub Kicinski <kuba@kernel.org>
Acked-by: Davide Benini <davide.benini@suse.com>

---
 net/ipv6/ip6_output.c |   10 ++++++----
 1 file changed, 6 insertions(+), 4 deletions(-)

--- a/net/ipv6/ip6_output.c
+++ b/net/ipv6/ip6_output.c
@@ -1241,7 +1241,7 @@ static int __ip6_append_data(struct sock
 			     struct page_frag *pfrag,
 			     int getfrag(void *from, char *to, int offset,
 					 int len, int odd, struct sk_buff *skb),
-			     void *from, int length, int transhdrlen,
+			     void *from, size_t length, int transhdrlen,
 			     unsigned int flags, struct ipcm6_cookie *ipc6,
 			     const struct sockcm_cookie *sockc)
 {
@@ -1559,6 +1559,7 @@ int ip6_append_data(struct sock *sk,
 	struct ipv6_pinfo *np = inet6_sk(sk);
 	int exthdrlen;
 	int err;
+	size_t ulength = length;
 
 	if (flags&MSG_PROBE)
 		return 0;
@@ -1572,7 +1573,7 @@ int ip6_append_data(struct sock *sk,
 			return err;
 
 		exthdrlen = (ipc6->opt ? ipc6->opt->opt_flen : 0);
-		length += exthdrlen;
+		ulength += exthdrlen;
 		transhdrlen += exthdrlen;
 	} else {
 		fl6 = &inet->cork.fl.u.ip6;
@@ -1581,7 +1582,7 @@ int ip6_append_data(struct sock *sk,
 
 	return __ip6_append_data(sk, fl6, &sk->sk_write_queue, &inet->cork.base,
 				 &np->cork, sk_page_frag(sk), getfrag,
-				 from, length, transhdrlen, flags, ipc6, sockc);
+				 from, ulength, transhdrlen, flags, ipc6, sockc);
 }
 EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL(ip6_append_data);
 
@@ -1746,6 +1747,7 @@ struct sk_buff *ip6_make_skb(struct sock
 	struct sk_buff_head queue;
 	int exthdrlen = (ipc6->opt ? ipc6->opt->opt_flen : 0);
 	int err;
+	size_t ulength = length;
 
 	if (flags & MSG_PROBE)
 		return NULL;
@@ -1767,7 +1769,7 @@ struct sk_buff *ip6_make_skb(struct sock
 
 	err = __ip6_append_data(sk, fl6, &queue, &cork.base, &v6_cork,
 				&current->task_frag, getfrag, from,
-				length + exthdrlen, transhdrlen + exthdrlen,
+				ulength + exthdrlen, transhdrlen + exthdrlen,
 				flags, ipc6, sockc);
 	if (err) {
 		__ip6_flush_pending_frames(sk, &queue, &cork, &v6_cork);
